: ~~Bold of you to assume I have friends.~~ Assuming your friends are up for it, this is probably the most realistic alternative until restaurants catch on. As my friend circle has shrunk it's rare to pull off "just a taste" splits with a table of 4-6, but whenever I grab dinner with my bestest of friends we do tend to swap whatever we order. Now if only they had half portions and we could order two each...

; Try a food walk.
: Like most sizable cities, Seattle has no shortage of yearly food events -- [[Ballard SeafoodFest|https://www.seafoodfest.org/]], [[Bite of Seattle|https://biteofseattle.com/]], [[CID Food Walk|https://www.seattlechinatownid.com/experiences/food-walk-series]], [[Fremont Fair|https://fremontfair.com/]], and [[Panda Fest|https://www.pandafests.com/]], just to name a few. Some of these do offer small plates ($6 from select vendors at the Bite, and $8 items at CID), but most vendors still sell full portions (like [[whatever the hell this is|https://fremontoktoberfest.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/22FOKT_SPONSOR-037.jpg]] for $18). I never understood this: why go to a place with 20-30 tents/trucks, only to fill up at maybe one or two of them?

; You literally just described Genki Sushi.
: True, [[Genki Sushi|https://www.genkisushiusa.com/]] and other [[conveyor belt sushi|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conveyor_belt_sushi]] chains are exactly what I want: $2-6 plates of 1-3 pieces each, mix and match to your heart's content. Now can we get this for a steakhouse? An Italian restaurant? A wing spot?